    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. In structural engineering, reinforced concrete is used because concrete is strong in compression but weak in tension. When concrete is subjected to tensile forces, it can crack and fail. Steel rebar, on the other hand, has high tensile strength and can withstand these forces without failing. By embedding steel rebar within the concrete, we create a composite material that can resist both compressive and tensile forces. This combination allows reinforced concrete to be used in a wide range of structural applications, including foundations, beams, and columns, where it can support heavy loads and resist various stresses. The steel rebar provides the tensile strength needed to counteract the tensile forces that would otherwise cause the concrete to crack and fail.",
